Other areas of the southwestern desert, including the Central Rockies and the Great Basin, could record 25 to 50 mm, with the possibility of isolated points of up to 100 mm.
For areas that are out of risk of flooding, the Rosa rain could become very good news, as the region is suffering from a severe drought.
Although flooding is a serious cause for concern, some of the rainfall could prove very beneficial, as the southwest region is currently suffering from a drought.
According to the U.S. Drought Control Service, more than 40 percent of the state of Arizona suffers from at least extreme drought, the second-highest category, reports weather.com.
But first, Hurricane Rosa will make landfall on the Baja California peninsula in Mexico.
