While Ri echoed North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a phased denuclearization approach that would reward North Korea as it took steps gradually, his statements seemed significant because he did not reject unilateral denuclearization outright, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to the joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work on the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula", while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has tried to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has communicated that Pyongyang must first eliminate its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease the tough international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The US insists that denuclearization must happen first and increases the pressure level with sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive way, in addition to opposing the 'declaration of end of war,'" Ri said.
The perception that sanctions will bring us to our knees is a chimera of people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the continuing sanctions are intensifying our distrust.
Ri did not refer to plans for a second Kim-Trump summit that the US leader highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months and added: If the party involved in the denuclearization issue was South Korea instead of the US, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have reached this stalemate situation.
However, the tone of Ri's speech was very different from what he maintained last year, when he declared to the UN General Assembly that targeting US territory with North Korean missiles was inevitable after President Mr. Evil Trump dubbed Kim Rocket Man on a suicide mission.
At the United Nations last year, Trump, who threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said there was still much to do and sanctions must be maintained until North Korea denuclearized.
