Harvard students are teaching a class on rest habits.
This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep more, in an attempt to combat the increasingly widespread culture of studying all night, stimulated by caffeine.
One scholar observed that students at the world's number one university are often clueless about the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after giving a talk about the impact sleep deprivation had on learning.
At the end of the talk, a girl came up to me and said, "Why am I being told this now, in my senior year?"
He said that no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, first implemented this year, explains the basics of how good sleep habits improve academic and athletic performance, as well as overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after learning that some students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive assignments.
In one section is a picture of a bedroom, where students are asked to click on coffee cups, curtains, blankets, and books to receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, about how sports performance affects sleep deprivation, and about the importance of maintaining a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Next, a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
We know that student behavior will not change immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know, as one has a right to know about the health effects of smoking cigarettes", Professor Czeisler pointed out.
The culture of pride in staying up all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure on students make sleep deprivation an increasing problem.
Ensuring good quality sleep for long enough should be a secret weapon of students to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he added, even to avoid gaining weight, since sleep deprivation puts the brain into a sleep mode and makes students always hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies Chemistry and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, after attending one of his classes in his senior year during his freshman year at Harvard.
Raymond commented that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote the course throughout the campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
