The National Foundation spies on the secret lives of bats
A new study on a farm in the Scottish Highlands aims to discover how bats use the landscape to feed.
It is hoped that the findings may provide new data on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help in future conservation activities.
The study by scientists from the National Foundation of Scotland will continue soprano and common bats, as well as northern eared bats and water bats at the Inverewe Botanic Garden, located in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations on the property to track the activities of the bats during the season.
Volunteers and staff from the UK National Health Service will also conduct mobile surveys with portable detectors.
Sound analysis of the recordings by experts will determine the frequency of the bats' sounds and what each species does.
With this information, a report and a habitat map will be created to create a detailed, landscape-scale image of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at the National Trust for Scotland, hopes the results will show which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation, and how to improve forest maintenance for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the rest of the UK has declined considerably over the last century.
Building and restoration tasks threaten bats, as they affect nests and can cause habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting also pose a risk, as do fly-paper and chemical treatments used in building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Actually, bats are not blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when they have to catch prey.
They use a sophisticated technique of echo-location to locate insects and obstacles that interfere with their flight.
The National Trust for Scotland, responsible for over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten experts with adequate training, who conduct surveys, nest inspections and, sometimes, rescues on a routine basis.
In fact, the organisation has created Scotland's first and only bat reserve at Threave Estate, located in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The farm's administrator, David Thompson, claims that it is the ideal territory for the species.
"Here in Threave, we have a large bat area", he says.
We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all good habitats.
But we still don't know a lot about bats, so the work we're doing here and at other properties will help us better understand what they need to grow.
It points out the importance of checking for bats before doing maintenance work on property, as the possible unintentional destruction of a single mothering nest may kill more than 400 females and juveniles, which could lead to the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, attack, harass, and destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an officer of the Scottish Bat Conservation Foundation, has encouraged people to step up and help.
He said, "We still have a lot to learn from bats, and for some of our species, we don't have enough data on their populations".
