Red tide update: concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in certain parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more dispersed proliferation conditions are being reported in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier areas, suggesting a lower concentration.
The red tide proliferation extends along approximately 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee counties.
Spots can be found 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places, compared to last week's situation.
The red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
There have been reports of mid-coast or offshore concentrations in Pinellas County over the past week, low-to-high-coast concentrations in Hillsborough County, bottom-to-high concentrations in Manatee County, mid-to-bottom concentrations in Charlotte County, bottom-to-high-coast or offshore concentrations in Lee County and low concentrations in Collier County.
Breathing irritations continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported over the past week in northeast Florida.
